Hierarchical Clustering¶

Hierarchical clustering is the cluster method that does not need to determine the number of clusters, because it is a bottom-up algorithm linking the elements from the minimal level and form the clusters step by step from bottom to up.

In detail, first, we treated each data point as single cluster. Hence, we will have 178 clusters at start. The number of data points will also be 178 at start. Then, we formed a big cluster by repeating to join two closet datapoints with centroid linkage. Finally, we got the two dendrograms.

Silhouette¶

Besides elbow method, silhouette score is a more straightforward way to determine the number of clusters. Silhouette score is the mean silhouette coefficient of all samples.An example's silhouette coefficient is equal to (b-a)/max(a,b),where a is the mean distance to other samples in the same cluster and b is the mean intra-cluster distance.

In [33]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

scores=[]
range_values=np.arange(2,10)
for i in range_values:
    kmeans=KMeans(init='k-means++',n_clusters=i,max_iter=300,n_init=10,random_state=0)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    score=silhouette_score(X,kmeans.labels_,metric='euclidean',sample_size=len(X))
    scores.append(score)

# Silhouette diagram is a more intuitive way to show the silhouette coefficient for every samples. The silhouette coefficients are sorted by the their values in the group of the cluster number.

# First, we draw the silhouette diagram for 3 clusters.

km = KMeans(n_clusters=3, 
            init='k-means++', 
            n_init=10, 
            max_iter=300,
            tol=1e-04,
            random_state=0)
y_km = km.fit_predict(X) # Use K-means devide the samples into 3 groups.

cluster_labels = np.unique(y_km)
n_clusters = cluster_labels.shape[0]
silhouette_vals = silhouette_samples(X, y_km, metric='euclidean')  # Return the silhouette coefficients for all samples

# Let's plot the silhouette diagram.

y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper = 0, 0 
yticks = []
for i, c in enumerate(cluster_labels): # A loop to draw the silhouette coefficients for each cluster
    c_silhouette_vals = silhouette_vals[y_km == c]
    c_silhouette_vals.sort()
    y_ax_upper += len(c_silhouette_vals)
    color = cm.jet(float(i) / n_clusters)
    plt.barh(range(y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper), c_silhouette_vals, height=1.0, 
             edgecolor='none', color=color)

    yticks.append((y_ax_lower + y_ax_upper) / 2.)
    y_ax_lower += len(c_silhouette_vals)
    
silhouette_avg = np.mean(silhouette_vals) # Use the dotted line to represent silhouette score 
plt.axvline(silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--") 

plt.yticks(yticks, cluster_labels + 1)
plt.ylabel('Cluster')
plt.xlabel('Silhouette coefficient')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
print('avg:',silhouette_avg)
print('min:',silhouette_vals.min())
print('max:',silhouette_vals.max())

Summary¶

In this project, we first make some descriptive analysis, drawing some plots, like the box plot and histogram to see whether there exists the outliers and how the data distribute. We also draw a correlation matrix to show the correlations between variables.

To cluster the type of the wine into group, we use two different ways, K-means clustering and Hierarchical clustering. In the K-means clustering, we notice that the value of "Proline" is much larger than the others, which means that "Proline" can play a much more important role and this may effect the outcome of clustering, so we do the normalization first. Then we choose SSE as the evaluation standard and determine the number of k as 3 by refering to the elbow plot. To present the result of K-means clustering more clearly, we choose PCA to reduce the dimension of wine data set. We calculate the eigenvalues of the data set, draw the plot of individual and cumulative explained variance, and choose to transform the original multiple variables into seven variables. With the work of PCA, we get a clear plot of K-means clustering result.

We also use PCA to reduce the dimension in the Hierarchical clustering, since there are 13 variables in this data set and high dimensionality may bring some trouble for clustering. It is obviously that with PCA we can cluster the data in our expected way. These two ways have their advantage and disavantage,but they all show a similar resultdividing the data into three categories.

To verify our result, we choose silhouette score as reference. We compare the silhouette diagram for 3 and 4 clusters. Dividing samples into 3 clusters indeed performs much better. This result coincides with the actual situation that the wine come from 3 cultivars.
